          "content": "In this lesson, we dive into the challenging world of predicting how much money we might make from our investments in the future. This task is much trickier than many people realize! To help us understand, we will explore the story of an economist named Irving Fisher. Back in 1929, he confidently stated that stock prices were at a 'permanently high plateau.' Unfortunately, this prediction came just before one of the biggest market crashes in history! Fisher's experience teaches us an important lesson: even the smartest analysts can have a tough time predicting what will happen in the stock market in the short term.\nBut don’t worry! While short-term predictions can be very uncertain, we can still make educated guesses about how our investments might perform over the long run. One helpful tool we can use is a formula called the Gordon equation. This equation tells us that the expected return on an investment can be estimated by adding the dividend yield (which is the money we earn from dividends) to the growth rate of those dividends (how much the dividends are expected to increase over time).\nLet’s break this down a bit more. When stocks are considered expensive, they usually have low dividend yields and high price-to-earnings (P/E) ratios. In this situation, we can expect lower returns in the future. On the other hand, when stocks are seen as cheap, they tend to have high dividend yields and low P/E ratios, which means we can expect higher returns.\nThe most important takeaway from this lesson is that while we can make rough predictions about how our investments will perform over many years, it’s crucial to be patient. The stock market can be unpredictable in the short term, but if we stay invested through all kinds of market conditions, we are more likely to see positive results over time. So, remember, investing is a long-term game, and staying the course can lead to rewards in the future!\nIn summary, predicting future returns is challenging, but by using tools like the Gordon equation and understanding market conditions, we can make better-informed decisions about our investments. Keep learning and stay curious about the world of investing!\nContext recap: In this lesson, we dive into the challenging world of predicting how much money we might make from our investments in the future. This task is much trickier than many people realize! To help us understand, we will explore the story of an economist named Irving Fisher. Back in 1929, he confidently stated that stock prices were at a 'permanently high plateau.' Unfortunately, this prediction came just before one of the biggest market crashes in history!\nWhy this matters: Measuring the Beast: Valuation and Expected Returns helps learners in Economics connect ideas from The Four Pillars of Investing: Lessons for Building a Winning Portfolio to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
