          "title": "The Efficient Market Hypothesis",
          "content": "In this lesson, we will explore the Efficient Market Hypothesis (EMH), which is an important concept in the world of finance. The EMH suggests that all publicly available information about a company is already included in its stock price. This means that if you are trying to find stocks that are priced lower than they should be (undervalued) or higher than they should be (overvalued) just by looking at the information that everyone else can see, it is very challenging to do so.\nTo understand this better, think of it like a game where everyone has the same information. If everyone knows the same facts about a company, then it’s tough for anyone to get an advantage by making decisions based on that information alone. This doesn’t mean that stock prices are always perfect or that they never make mistakes. Instead, it suggests that when prices are wrong, those mistakes are usually too small or happen too quickly for investors to take advantage of them. Additionally, when you consider the costs involved in buying and selling stocks, such as trading fees and taxes, it becomes even harder to profit from these small mistakes.\nResearch has shown that most actively managed mutual funds, which are funds where managers try to pick stocks to outperform the market, do not do better than their benchmark indices over time. A benchmark index is a standard against which the performance of a fund can be measured. In fact, many of these funds fail to beat the market consistently. Even the few funds that do well in one period are not guaranteed to continue performing well in the future. It’s almost like winning a game of chance; just because you win once doesn’t mean you will win again.\nBernstein, a well-known figure in finance, argues that the financial industry continues to promote active management not because it is necessarily better for investors, but because it allows them to charge higher fees. This means that while investors might think they are getting a better deal with actively managed funds, they might actually be paying more for something that doesn’t provide better results.\nBy understanding the Efficient Market Hypothesis, investors can make more informed decisions about how to manage their money. They can consider whether it might be wiser to invest in passive strategies, which typically involve lower fees and aim to match market performance rather than trying to beat it. This knowledge can empower investors to choose options that align with their financial goals and help them grow their wealth over time.\nContext recap: In this lesson, we will explore the Efficient Market Hypothesis (EMH), which is an important concept in the world of finance. The EMH suggests that all publicly available information about a company is already included in its stock price. This means that if you are trying to find stocks that are priced lower than they should be (undervalued) or higher than they should be (overvalued) just by looking at the information that everyone else can see, it is very challenging to do so. To understand this better, think of it like a game where everyone has the same information.\nWhy this matters: The Efficient Market Hypothesis helps learners in Economics connect ideas from The Four Pillars of Investing: Lessons for Building a Winning Portfolio to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
