          "title": "A History of Manias: From Tulips to Tech Stocks",
          "content": "In this lesson, we will dive into the fascinating history of speculative manias, which are crucial for anyone looking to invest wisely over the long term. The author, Bernstein, highlights several notable examples from history that illustrate how these manias occur and what we can learn from them. One of the earliest examples is the Dutch Tulip Mania of 1637, where the prices of tulip bulbs skyrocketed to unbelievable heights before crashing down. Then, there was the South Sea Bubble in 1720, where investors were drawn into a frenzy over shares in a company that promised riches from trade in the South Seas. Fast forward to the 1840s, and we see the Railway Mania, where the excitement over new railroads led to inflated stock prices. The Roaring Twenties brought another stock market boom, fueled by optimism and speculation, only to be followed by the Great Depression. Lastly, the dot-com bubble of the late 1990s saw many people investing in internet companies, believing they would change the world forever, until the bubble burst and many lost their investments.\nDespite the years that separate these events, they all share some striking similarities. They often start with a groundbreaking technology or significant economic change that seems to justify the high prices investors are willing to pay. Early investors usually see huge profits, which attracts even more people to jump on the bandwagon. A common mindset during these times is the belief that 'this time is different' — that the usual rules of investing no longer apply because the new technology or idea is so revolutionary. This leads many inexperienced investors to enter the market, often using borrowed money to do so. Eventually, these manias reach a dramatic peak, where prices are at their highest, but this is often followed by a sharp crash that can wipe out the wealth of those who invested at the last minute. By understanding these patterns and the psychology behind them, investors can better navigate the market and avoid repeating the mistakes of the past. Learning from history is a powerful tool in the world of investing, and it can help you make more informed decisions in your own investment journey.\nContext recap: In this lesson, we will dive into the fascinating history of speculative manias, which are crucial for anyone looking to invest wisely over the long term. The author, Bernstein, highlights several notable examples from history that illustrate how these manias occur and what we can learn from them. One of the earliest examples is the Dutch Tulip Mania of 1637, where the prices of tulip bulbs skyrocketed to unbelievable heights before crashing down. Then, there was the South Sea Bubble in 1720, where investors were drawn into a frenzy over shares in a company that promised riches from trade in the South Seas.\nWhy this matters: A History of Manias: From Tulips to Tech Stocks helps learners in Economics connect ideas from The Four Pillars of Investing: Lessons for Building a Winning Portfolio to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
